{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496822"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.11,0.05,0.21,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57978"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43437"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57978"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man admitted for community-acquired pneumonia complains of new-onset shortness of breath and crushing chest pain. His medical history includes diet-controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, high cholesterol, and rheumatoid arthritis. His regular medications include daily amlodipine, atorvastatin, and weekly methotrexate. He used to be a heavy smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 56 beats/min and blood pressure is 86/64 mmHg. Oxygen saturation is 97% on room air, with a respiratory rate of 22/min. His ECG shows ST segment elevation in the inferior leads and right-sided precordial leads and ST depression in the V2-V3 consistent with an acute ST elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) involving the right ventricle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the 1st step in management of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer intravenous fluids","Administer nitrates","Administer beta-blockers","Perform immediate percutaneous coronary intervention","Administer thrombolytics"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadminister intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient is in cardiogenic shock, as indicated by hypotension and bradycardia, with ST elevation myocardial infarction (STEMI) changes on ECG, which are suggestive of a right ventricular infarction. In right ventricular infarction, the heart relies on adequate preload to maintain cardiac output. Administering intravenous fluids helps to increase preload and improve blood pressure in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering nitrates\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in right ventricular infarction because they can cause a significant drop in blood pressure by reducing preload, which can worsen hypotension and compromise cardiac output.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering beta-blockers\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this scenario due to the patient\u0027s bradycardia and hypotension. Beta-blockers can further decrease heart rate and blood pressure, exacerbating the patient\u0027s condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming immediate percutaneous coronary intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is an important step in the management of STEMI, but the most urgent initial step in this case is to stabilise the patient\u0027s haemodynamics with fluids, at PCI can take up to 30 -60 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering thrombolytics\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in the management of STEMI if percutaneous coronary intervention is not immediately available. However, the immediate priority in this scenario is to address the hypotension with fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiogenic shock is characterised by inadequate tissue perfusion due to cardiac dysfunction, often requiring fluid resuscitation to support circulation.","Right ventricular infarction requires careful management of preload to maintain cardiac output."],"references":["Somers MP, Brady WJ, Bateman DC, Mattu A, Perron AD. Additional electrocardiographic leads in the ED chest pain patient: right ventricular and posterior leads. The American journal of emergency medicine. 2003 Nov;21(7):563\u201373","Kosaraju A, Pendela VS, Hai O. Cardiogenic Shock. [Updated 2023 Apr 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482255/","Vahdatpour C, Collins D, Goldberg S. Cardiogenic Shock. J Am Heart Assoc. 2019 Apr 16;8(8):e011991. doi: 10.1161/JAHA.119.011991. PMID: 30947630; PMCID: PMC6507212.","Femia G, French JK, Juergens C, Leung D, Lo S. Right ventricular myocardial infarction: pathophysiology, clinical implications and management. Rev Cardiovasc Med. 2021 Dec 22;22(4):1229-1240. doi: 10.31083/j.rcm2204131. PMID: 34957766."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43437"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43437"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T15:23:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T15:24:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57978"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1674","links":{"s